member.name: T:GotDotNet.Exslt.MultiXmlTextWriter

summary.para: MultiXmlTextWriter class extends standard XmlTextWriter class and represents an XML writer that provides a fast, non-cached, forward-only way of generating multiple output files containing either text data or XML data that conforms to the W3C Extensible Markup Language (XML) 1.0 and the Namespaces in XML recommendations.

remarks.para: Instances of MultiXmlTextWriter class regognize special element (<exsl:document> in "http://exslt.org/common" namespace) as instruction to redirect the output of this element's content to another file. When using with XslTransform class, MultiXmlTextWriter class allows to generate multiple XSL Transfromation results.

MultiXmlTextWriter class extends System.Xml.XmlTextWriter class, therefore its instances can be passed directly to the overloaded XslTransform.Transform() method, which accepts XmlWriter as object to write the transformation result to. All actual XML writing work MultiXmlTextWriter class delegates to its base class, but it overrides several XmlTextWriter class methods to implement output switching logic as follows: once <exsl:document> element start tag is detected in the XML stream, new writer (XmlTextWriter or StreamWriter depending on method attribute value) object is created with parameters as specified in the attributes of the <exsl:document> element and the output is switched to this newly created writer untill the end tag of the <exsl:document> element is encountered.

<exsl:document> element syntax is as follows:
             
             <exsl:document
                href = { uri-reference }
                method = { "xml" | "text" }
                encoding = { string }
                standalone = { "yes" | "no" }
                doctype-public = { string }
                doctype-system = { string }
                indent = { "yes" | "no" }
                <-- Content: template -->
             </exsl:document>

The href attribute specifies where new result document should be stored, it must be an absolute or relative URI. Relative URIs are resolved relatively to the parent result document base URI. If the href attribute specifies that the output should be redirected to a file in a directory and that directory does not exist, it will be created. This allows to create directory trees of any complexity.
Semantics of the rest attributes is as defined in W3C XSLT 1.0 Recommendation for <xsl:output> element, see http://www.w3.org/TR/xslt.html#output.
Note: <exsl:document> element namespace prefix must be bound to "http://exslt.org/common" namespace URI in order to be recognized by MultiXmlTextWriter class as a redirecting instruction.

member.example:
This example shows how to use MultiXmlTextWriter along with XslTransform to achieve create multiple result documents in one transfromation run: In XSL stylesheet document declare "http://exslt.org/common" namespace and whenever you want to create new result document make use of element: style.xsl stylesheet fragment: <xsl:value-of select="@title"/> Table of Contents
... C# code fragment: XPathDocument doc = new XPathDocument("book.xml"); XslTransform xslt = new XslTransform(); xslt.Load("style.xsl"); MultiXmlTextWriter multiWriter = new MultiXmlTextWriter("index.html", Encoding.UTF8); multiWriter.Formatting = Formatting.Indented; xslt.Transform(doc, null, multiWriter);
